body:
I think its looking for files with extension ```.mjs``` and ```.cjs``` in all the  directories inside eslint codebase,  for the unit tests  the globbyPatterns array is ```[ '**/*.js', '**/*.mjs', '**/*.cjs', 'tools/*.js', 'tests/**/*.js' ]```  and for  ```'**/*.mjs'``` and ```'**/*.cjs'``` we are not specifying directory path hence globby is returning empty array which means no related filepath is found. For ```'**/*.js'``` also we are not specifying any directory path but that is not giving error since '.js' files are present.


I am doing something like this:

```
const globbyResults = [];

    if (globbyPatterns.length) {
        for (let i = 0; i < globbyPatterns.length; i++) {
            const SingleGlobbyResult = await globby(globbyPatterns[i], {
                cwd,
                absolute: true,
                ignore: configs.ignores.filter(
                    matcher => typeof matcher === "string"
                )
            });

            if (!SingleGlobbyResult.length) {
                throw new NoFilesFoundError(globbyPatterns[i], globInputPaths);
            } else {
                globbyResults.push(...SingleGlobbyResult);
            }
        }
    }
```

Thanks for taking a stab at this. It’s pretty complex logic so it’s easy to get lost in there. Definitely not a gentle landing spot for a new contributor.

@mdjermanovic is correct: we don’t want every glob pattern to throw if there’s not a match. This particular issue points out that an explicit glob pattern passed on the command line that has no match should throw an error.

I think we should have a separate discussion about how to handle when a directory is passed because this works differently than it did with eslintrc.
